5 "Part 2. Appointment Types.
6 "§ 126A-10. Appointment types.
7 (a) All employees are assigned a position with a designated appointment type.
8 (1) A position is the unique duties and responsibilities of a job to which a person
9 is assigned.
10 (2) An appointment type defines the terms and expected duration of employment,
11 benefits eligibility, and the applicability of this Chapter to the position.
12 (b) Appointment types are as follows:
13 (1) Permanent. – An appointment to a permanent position established and
14 expected to continue indefinitely. All permanent employees are designated as
15 one of the following subcategories:
16 a. Career appointment. – Assigned to an employee who has been
17 continuously employed for the time period provided in
18 G.S. 126A-10.1.
19 b. Probationary appointment. – Assigned to an employee who has not
20 been continuously employed long enough to become a career
21 employee under G.S. 126A-10.1.
22 c. Permanent experiential appointment. – Assigned to an employee in an
23 experiential program who has not been continuously employed long
24 enough to become a career employee under G.S. 126A-10.1.
25 (2) Non-permanent. – An appointment to a position for a finite period of time. All
26 non-permanent employees are designated as one of the following
27 subcategories:
28 a. Temporary appointment. – Assigned to an employee employed for a
29 period typically not to exceed 11 months.
30 b. Time-limited appointment. – Assigned to an employee employed in a
31 position that has a limited period not to exceed three years.
32 c. Non-permanent experiential appointment. – Assigned to an employee
33 in an experiential program for a limited period of time.
34 (3) Exempt. – An appointment to a position designated by statute as exempt as
35 defined in G.S. 126A-15. An exempt appointment may be made to a
36 permanent or time-limited position.
37 (c) An employee who moves from a non-permanent or exempt appointment to a
38 permanent appointment shall have a probationary appointment for at least 12 months.
39 (d) The following exceptions apply:
40 (1) When a time-limited appointment exceeds three years, the employee shall be
41 designated as having a permanent appointment and, notwithstanding
42 subsection (c) of this section, shall not be required to have a probationary
43 appointment.
44 (2) A time-limited appointment may be made to a permanent position only when
45 that position is vacant due to the incumbent's leave of absence and the
46 replacement employee's services will be needed for a period of one year or
47 less.
48 (3) A career employee who is assigned a position that is designated as exempt
49 under G.S. 126A-15(1)a., 126A-15(2), and 126A-15(3) may, once that
50 employee is no longer in the designated exempt position, be reassigned as a
Senate Bill 1041-Second Edition Page 3

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 career employee with no probationary period if the employee remains
2 continuously employed by the State.
3 (e) Except for career and probationary appointments, the appointment types in this
4 section do not apply to local employees.
5 "§ 126A-10.1. Qualification as career employee.
6 (a) An employee in a probationary appointment shall be assigned a career appointment
7 as follows:
8 (1) An employee who successfully completes 12 months of employment in a
9 probationary appointment shall be assigned a career appointment except as
10 provided in subdivisions (2) and (3) of this subsection. The employee shall be
11 assigned a career appointment unless there is a supervisory extension of the
12 probationary period or separation based on performance or conduct prior to
13 the completion of the 12 months of employment.
14 (2) If the employee's supervisor determines an additional six-month period is
15 needed to assess whether the employee's performance in the probationary
16 appointment is successful or needs improvement, the employee who
17 successfully completes a total of 18 months of probationary appointment shall
18 be assigned a career appointment.
19 (3) An employee hired in a sworn law enforcement position or forensic scientist
20 position who is required to complete a formal training program prior to
21 assuming law enforcement or forensic scientist duties with the employing
22 agency shall be assigned a career appointment only after being employed by
23 the agency for 24 continuous months in a probationary appointment. An
24 employee who has a career appointment retains that appointment if the
25 employee transfers from a position that does not require completion of a
26 formal training program into a position under this subdivision that does
27 require a formal training program, even if the employee has worked for the
28 agency for fewer than 24 continuous months.
29 (b) An employee in a permanent experiential appointment shall be assigned a career
30 appointment as follows:
31 (1) For experiential programs of 12 months or longer, an employee who
32 successfully completes an experiential program in a permanent experiential
33 appointment shall be assigned a career appointment. The employee shall be
34 assigned a career appointment unless there is a separation based on
35 performance or conduct prior to the completion of the experiential program.
36 (2) For experiential programs of less than 12 months, an employee who
37 successfully completes the experiential program shall be assigned a
38 probationary appointment and shall receive a career appointment as provided
39 in subsection (a) of this section.
40 (c) When an employee transfers employment between two local agencies, or between an
41 executive branch agency and a local agency, that employee resets the period of consecutive
42 service required in subsection (a) of this section.
43 (d) Employees of The University of North Carolina who are exempt from the minimum
44 wage and overtime compensation provisions of the Fair Labor Standards Act and who attained
45 career status before September 1, 2023, have the option of either (i) continuing employment with
46 a career employee appointment if the employee remains in the position the employee occupied
47 on August 31, 2023, or (ii) waiving the career employee appointment and continuing employment
48 as a statutorily exempt employee, as defined in Part 3 of this Article. The University shall provide
49 each affected employee with a written explanation of the impact of an election to waive the career
50 employee appointment. An employee's election to waive the career employee appointment must
