8 May 1 and November 1 of each year.
9 "§ 126A-85. Alternative dispute resolution.
10 (a) The Commission may adopt policies on alternative dispute resolution procedures for
11 the resolution of matters constituting grounds for a grievance under this Article.
12 (b) The Commission may adopt policies on alternative dispute resolution procedures for
13 matters not constituting grounds for a grievance under this Article that cannot be heard by the
14 Office of Administrative Hearings as a contested case.
15 "§ 126A-86. Judicial review of fee awards.
16 A decision of the Office of Administrative Hearings on whether to assess reasonable
17 witnesses' fees or a reasonable attorneys' fee shall be subject to judicial review in accordance
18 with G.S. 126A-84(b). The reviewing court may reverse or modify the decision of the Office of
19 Administrative Hearings if the decision is unreasonable or the award is inadequate. An employee
20 who obtains a reversal or modification of the Office of Administrative Hearings' decision in an
21 appeal under this section shall be entitled to recover court costs and a reasonable attorneys' fee
22 for representation in connection with the appeal.
23 "Article 9.
24 "Separation, Offboarding, and Reductions in Force.
25 "§ 126A-90. Separation of employees.
26 The Commission shall establish policies on separation for positions subject to this Article,
27 including the following:
28 (1) The separation of employees.
29 (2) Voluntary separation incentives.
30 (3) Furloughs of employees by placing them on temporary leave without pay in
31 response to a loss of funding.
32 (4) Reductions in force.
33 "§ 126A-91. Voluntary separation incentives.
34 An agency may reorganize and restructure its positions through a voluntary separation
35 process that provides incentives to separate in accordance with Commission policy and subject
36 to approval by the Office of State Budget and Management.
37 "§ 126A-92. Reductions in force.
38 (a) Usage. – Agencies may use a reduction in force to reorganize its positions to better
39 accomplish its functions or respond to a lack of work or shortage of funds. Agencies may use a
40 reduction in force without a loss of funds and without eliminating any of the positions affected
41 by the reduction in force.
42 (b) Notification. – Agencies shall notify employees to be affected by a reduction in force
43 as soon as practicable and at least 30 days before the effective date of the reduction in force.
44 "§ 126A-93. Reductions in force priority policy.
45 The Commission shall adopt policies governing the priority and salary rights of employees
46 separated as a result of reduction in force. The policies shall provide that a separated employee
47 who accepts a position in an agency shall not be paid a salary higher than the maximum of the
48 salary range of the position accepted, except as provided in G.S. 126A-41.
49 "§ 126A-94. Discontinued service retirement allowance and severance wages for certain
50 employees.
