1
2 EFFECT ON AGREEMENTS AND PENDING LITIGATION
3 SECTION 5.3.(a) All decentralization agreements, delegation agreements, and
4 memoranda of understanding between the Office of State Human Resources and any agency,
5 department, or institution in effect on September 30, 2026, shall remain in effect until modified
6 or terminated in accordance with the terms of those agreements of memoranda or superseded by
7 agreements executed under the authority of Chapter 126A of the General Statutes, as enacted by
8 this act.
9 SECTION 5.3.(b) No action or proceeding brought by or against the State Human
10 Resources Commission or the Office of State Human Resources, or against the State of North
11 Carolina concerning either the State Human Resources Commission or the Office of State Human
12 Resources, that is pending on October 1, 2026, shall be abated, suspended, or otherwise affected
13 by the enactment of this act. Any such action or proceeding shall be prosecuted or defended under
14 the law applicable at the time the action or proceeding was initiated, provided that nothing in this
15 subsection shall preclude any party from citing provisions for persuasive guidance where the
16 language of Chapter 126A of the General Statutes, as enacted by this act, and Chapter 126 of the
17 General Statutes as it exists on September 30, 2026, is identical or substantially identical.
18
19 CLASSIFICATION AND COMPENSATION ASSESSMENT
20 SECTION 5.4.(a) The Office of State Human Resources shall assess the State's
21 classification and compensation system and identify opportunities for improvement, consulting
22 with agencies and outside experts, as needed. By October 1, 2027, the Office of State Human
23 Resources shall report its findings and recommendations to the chairs of the Senate
24 Appropriations/Base Budget Committee, the chairs of the House Appropriations Committee, the
25 Joint Legislative Commission on Governmental Operations pursuant to G.S. 120-36.7, and the
26 Fiscal Research Division.
27 SECTION 5.4.(b) By March 1, 2027, and annually thereafter, each executive branch
28 agency shall report the following information to the Office of State Human Resources, upon
29 request:
30 (1) The five job classifications most difficult to recruit and retain during the prior
31 fiscal year.
32 (2) Actions taken to address those challenges, including requests for
33 reclassification, pay adjustments, or other flexibilities from the Office of State
34 Human Resources.
35 (3) Whether existing classification or compensation policies constrained the
36 agency's ability to address those challenges, and if so, how.
37 SECTION 5.4.(c) The Office of State Human Resources shall incorporate trends and
38 recommended legislative actions from this assessment into the annual State of the State
39 workforce report required by G.S. 126A-24.
40 SECTION 5.4.(d) Following the initial assessment and review of agency data, the
41 Office of State Human Resources shall contemplate executing a pilot on classification and
42 compensation recommendations in one or more executive branch agencies that volunteer to
43 participate. The purpose of the pilot is to test modifications to classification and compensation
44 practices, including alternative job titling, revised qualification standards, or adjusted pay-setting
45 flexibility, that the Office of State Human Resources determines are likely to improve
46 recruitment, retention, or time-to-hire outcomes.
47
48 DEVELOP IMPROVED WORKFORCE ACCOUNTABILITY SYSTEM
49 SECTION 5.5. By December 1, 2026, the Office of State Human Resources shall
50 submit to the State Human Resources Commission and the Governor a revised disciplinary policy
51 containing an improved process for managing State employee performance and conduct. The
Senate Bill 1041-Second Edition Page 73

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 State Human Resources Commission, subject to the approval of the Governor, shall adopt a
2 revised Disciplinary Action Policy by April 1, 2027.
3
4 STATE OF THE STATE WORKFORCE REPORT
5 SECTION 5.6. The Office of State Human Resources shall submit the first State of
6 the State workforce report required by G.S. 126A-24 by January 15, 2027.
7
8 PART VI. EFFECTIVE DATE
